{"componentChunkName":"component---src-templates-chapter-level-2-chapter-level-2-tsx","path":"/topics/itch-widespread/diagnosis/history-examination/","result":{"pageContext":{"chapter":{"id":"1cf86197-a1ad-58fc-b46d-d2814ed58a17","slug":"history-examination","fullItemName":"History and examination","depth":2,"htmlHeader":"<!-- begin field 50ff6c88-5164-4d01-957a-c3576e15a1be --><h2>What should I ask and look for on examination?</h2><!-- end field 50ff6c88-5164-4d01-957a-c3576e15a1be -->","summary":"","htmlStringContent":"<!-- begin item 514f2e83-e067-492e-b471-c44b9e2f7b16 --><!-- begin field fc838974-34b4-4aea-87da-2214ced86b99 --><ul><li><strong>Ask the person about:</strong><ul><li>The characteristics of the itch:<ul><li>Prickling &mdash; can persist for hours after a hot shower or bath in people with polycythaemia vera.</li><li>Crawling &mdash; itch described as &#39;like insects crawling over the skin&#39; may be psychogenic in origin and indicative of delusions of parasitosis.</li><li>Burning &mdash; may be a feature of dermatitis herpetiformis and some types of urticaria or lymphoma. Stinging after contact with water is known as aquagenic pruritus and may be an isolated symptom, although it can be associated with myeloproliferative disorders such as polycythaemia vera.</li><li>Onset, timing, and duration of itch &mdash; for example nocturnal itch can suggest scabies.</li><li>Location of itch &mdash; consistently localized itch suggests a localized cause rather than systemic disease.</li><li>Relieving factors &mdash; itch that is relieved with emollients or topical antipruritics is rarely associated with a serious cause.</li><li>Associated symptoms (for example rash, fever, weight loss).</li><li>Drug history (to exclude medications that can cause itching, for example opioids, statins, angiotensin-converting enzyme [ACE] inhibitors).</li><li>Diet &mdash; to identify features suggesting iron deficiency.</li><li>Itching in other people who have been contacts &mdash; may indicate scabies.</li><li>Alcohol misuse &mdash; may indicate liver disease.</li><li>Emotional stress and mental health history &mdash; may indicate a psychogenic cause.</li></ul></li></ul></li><li><strong>Review all systems to identify symptoms associated with <a class=\"topic-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/itch-widespread/background-information/causes/\">systemic disease</a>.</strong> This may help focus the physical examination and laboratory tests.</li><li><strong>A full physical examination may be useful if there are no localizing clues from the history.</strong> Always examine:<ul><li>The skin, for&nbsp;<ul><li>Lesions, rash, signs of infestation, or excoriation.</li><li>Dermographism (skin becomes raised and red when firmly stroked with a blunt object) &mdash; indicative of a type of urticaria.&nbsp;</li><li>Colour &mdash; may suggest jaundice, renal failure, or anaemia.&nbsp;</li></ul></li><li>Lymph nodes, for enlargement.&nbsp;&nbsp;</li><li>Liver and spleen, for enlargement.</li></ul></li></ul><!-- end field fc838974-34b4-4aea-87da-2214ced86b99 --><!-- end item 514f2e83-e067-492e-b471-c44b9e2f7b16 -->","topic":{"id":"98db983b-94d0-57fc-8f85-3c35dffdbc84","topicId":"3ff60e1b-3717-41cc-be12-1871b4284ba6","topicName":"Itch - widespread","slug":"itch-widespread","lastRevised":"Last revised in December 2016","chapters":[{"id":"c31a1ea7-3548-5767-9a55-10f56f4ea14a","fullItemName":"Summary","slug":"summary","subChapters":[]},{"id":"316853c8-d1ca-5613-8c4d-c33ea7c0fd8b","fullItemName":"Have I got the right topic?","slug":"have-i-got-the-right-topic","subChapters":[]},{"id":"64abf965-05aa-566d-999c-e216708a87b3","fullItemName":"How up-to-date is this topic?","slug":"how-up-to-date-is-this-topic","subChapters":[{"id":"d34f3906-2823-5407-8f4d-32157480544d","slug":"changes","fullItemName":"Changes"},{"id":"8981751b-abe1-515d-b935-74b8a9b645f8","slug":"update","fullItemName":"Update"}]},{"id":"e1e55a0f-0001-592a-92fd-aacfa519336f","fullItemName":